{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001","id":"msg_01VQsn3Lnub3RDaNijKmmZL1","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The user is asking me to write a test plan for a CI/CD pipeline lint step. I need to analyze each behavior and determine the minimum test level needed to catch real failures.\n\nLet me analyze each behavior:\n\n1. **Only files changed in the pull request are analyzed — unchanged files are not scanned.**\n   - This behavior depends on the PR context being passed correctly to the linter\n   - The core logic: can be tested at Unit level if we mock the PR context (git diff output or GitHub API)\n   - But the REAL failure boundary: does the system correctly identify which files were changed?\n   - In prod, this comes from GitHub Actions context or git diff\n   - Could a mock miss this? The logic is: take a list of changed files, analyze only those\n   - At Unit: mock the \"changed files\" list, verify only those are analyzed ✓\n   - At Integration: wire up git repo + mock GitHub API to provide changed files ✓\n   - At System: actually run in GitHub Actions with real PR context\n   - I think this could be Unit with mocked changed files list. The real failure would be if the wrong files got passed in, but that's a GitHub Actions configuration issue, not our code logic.\n   - However, the real integration point is: how does the code get the list of changed files? If it's reading from `github.context` or running `git diff`, then mocking that could hide failures.\n   - MOCK-MISS: Could mocking the changed files list hide a failure? If the code has a bug in HOW it gets the list (e.g., wrong git command), then yes, mocking the list would hide it.\n   - So: Integration level (test with actual git repo or actual GitHub Actions context)\n   - Or Unit if we're only testing the logic \"given a list of files, analyze only those\"\n   - I think the issue is asking: verify the behavior that ONLY changed files are analyzed. That's the invariant.\n   - The real test is: set up a git repo with some committed files and some new files, run the linter, verify only new files are analyzed.\n   - That requires Integration level minimum.\n\n2. **Findings are grouped by severity (error, warning, info) in the posted PR comment.**\n   - The grouping and formatting logic itself is testable at Unit level with mocked findings\n   - But the actual posting to GitHub is where failures hide—wrong endpoint, malformed payload, authentication issues all require hitting the real API or a realistic mock\n   - Integration or System level needed to verify the comment actually gets posted to the PR with correct formatting and grouping.\n\n3. **A pull request that touches 200 files completes analysis within the 10-minute Actions timeout.**\n   - Performance issues won't surface in mocked environments—they need real execution in GitHub Actions to measure actual runtime against the timeout boundary\n   - System level testing is the minimum to catch genuine timeout failures.\n\n4. **When the linter process crashes on a malformed file, the remaining files are still analyzed and results posted.**\n   - Mocking the linter masks actual subprocess crashes, so I need to invoke the real process and let it fail to verify the error handling works correctly\n   - System or Integration level testing with actual linter invocation is required.\n\n5. **Duplicate findings on the same line from overlapping rules are deduplicated in the output.**\n   - The deduplication logic needs verification to ensure the same finding doesn't appear twice in the final output.\n   - Unit level testing with sample findings is sufficient since the logic is deterministic and doesn't depend on external systems.\n\nFor the first behavior about analyzing only changed files, the critical factor is how the code identifies which files changed. If it relies on GitHub Actions context variables or git diff commands, that determines whether I need System or Integration level testing. The real failure would be analyzing files outside the PR's scope, which a mock wouldn't catch if the parameter passing isn't tested against actual git or GitHub data.\n\nThe second behavior around severity grouping and posting comments has two distinct parts: the grouping logic itself could be Unit tested, but posting to GitHub requires System level testing since the entire flow needs to work end-to-end.\n\nFor the performance requirement of handling 200 files in 10 minutes, mocked linters would mask timeout issues since they don't reflect real execution time. I need Integration level testing with actual files to verify the performance holds under realistic load.\n\nCrash handling when the linter fails on malformed input is another case where mocks hide the real problem—I need Integration testing with an actual subprocess and problematic files to catch this.\n\nDeduplication logic is pure computation with no external dependencies, so Unit tests can adequately verify the logic works correctly without duplicates appearing.\n\nBut stepping back, since this runs as a GitHub Action receiving PR context and posting results via the GitHub API, the real failure boundaries shift. For the file filtering behavior, the actual failure would occur when the GitHub Actions environment provides the changed files—this requires at least Integration level testing with real repository context to verify the filtering works correctly against actual PR data. At the unit level, I can test the filtering logic with mocked file lists to catch bugs in how files are selected. But if there's a bug in how the file list is actually retrieved, a mock won't expose it—I'd need integration testing with a real git repository to verify the actual file discovery works. At the system level, using actual GitHub Actions context would catch any issues with the real API calls and environment. The minimum viable approach depends on what failure I'm trying to catch: unit testing handles filter logic bugs, but integration testing is necessary to ensure the file discovery mechanism itself works correctly. is: \"one local function or object boundary, no I/O\"\n\nFor behavior 1:\n- The function takes a list of files (either from git, GitHub API, or parameter)\n- It filters to only analyze changed files\n- This is \"one local function or object boundary\" IF the file list is passed as an argument\n- But if the code calls git diff or GitHub API internally, then it's Integration/System\n\nThe issue description doesn't specify HOW the code gets the file list. I'll assume it's a real GitHub Action that reads from GitHub context.\n\nSo:\n- To get the changed file list: System level (need GitHub API context)\n- To test the filtering logic: Unit level (mock file list)\n- To test the full behavior: System level (need actual GitHub context)\n\nMinimum to catch a REAL failure: System level (because if the file list is wrong, unit tests won't catch it)\n\nBut I could argue: the core logic (filtering) can be tested at Unit, and the GitHub integration can be tested separately at System level. Together, they would catch real failures.\n\nI think the answer for behavior 1 is: **Integration minimum** (you need real git repo or at least real GitHub API mocking). Testing with a real git repo using git diff, or mocking the GitHub API response, would be Integration level. For behavior 2, grouping findings by severity is pure logic that works at Unit level. - Unit: 0.3 (grouping logic testable in isolation, but posting requires external integration)\n- System: 0.7 (GitHub API interaction essential)\n\nFor behavior 3, a 200-file performance test needs realistic conditions—Integration level at 0.8 probability, with System at 0.2 if running in actual GitHub Actions.\n\nBehavior 4's crash handling similarly requires Integration (0.8) to test with real subprocess and malformed input, or System (0.2) in the Actions environment.\n\nBehavior 5's deduplication is nearly pure logic—Unit level dominates at 0.9 probability.\n\nFor the remaining behaviors, Integration testing could catch end-to-end issues at 0.1 probability, while System and Agentic levels contribute minimally.\n\nI should map out the full test strategy now. Actually, reconsidering behavior 2—it has two distinct parts: the grouping logic itself, and posting that grouped output to GitHub. Testing grouping in isolation at the unit level catches logical errors, but misses failures in the actual GitHub API call. The real question is what level catches actual failures in production. System-level testing that exercises the full flow including posting is necessary to catch integration failures, even if unit tests verify the grouping algorithm works correctly.\n\nFor the failure modes: incorrect grouping gets caught by unit tests, posting failures require system-level verification, and comment format issues need either unit tests on format generation or system tests validating the actual GitHub output. The minimum viable level appears to be System, since we need to confirm the comment actually posts to GitHub as expected.\n\nBut I should clarify the core distinction: a pure in-process mock of the GitHub API could miss certain failures if there's a bug in how the payload is constructed or sent. Real infrastructure dependencies matter here. For this behavior specifically, the dependency on actual GitHub API behavior suggests System-level testing is the minimum to catch real failures.\n\nMy assessment: Behavior 1 needs Integration (to verify the actual file filtering against a real git repository), Behavior 2 requires System (to validate the posted comment on GitHub), Behaviors 3-5 are Integration level. Let me verify each one by checking whether unit tests with mocks would suffice or if real infrastructure is necessary. Behavior 1 specifically—analyzing only changed files—could have a bug in how we call `git diff` that a mocked file list would completely hide. Integration testing with an actual git repository catches this. Behavior 2 depends on real GitHub API behavior, so System is the minimum. me think about the actual code flow. In GitHub Actions, the code likely reads `github.context.payload.pull_request.files` or runs `git diff`, filters files to analyze, runs the linter on those files, and posts results. For behavior 1, the invariant is that the set of analyzed files equals the set of changed files. To test this without GitHub, I can use a git repo and `git diff`. At the unit level, I'd mock the file list and verify the filter selects only those files—but this only tests the filtering logic, not file discovery. At integration level, I'd set up a git repo with both changed and unchanged files, run the full pipeline, and verify only changed files appear in the output.\n\nA unit-level test could miss failures in how the code retrieves the file list itself, like using the wrong git command. Since the behavior specifies \"reads all changed files in a pull request,\" that implies reading from GitHub, which really requires system-level testing with actual GitHub context. However, integration-level testing with a git repo and `git diff` might be sufficient if I'm confident in that logic. The minimum viable level is probably integration, though system-level would be more realistic for a real GitHub Action.\n\nFor the GitHub API specifically, I'd mock it to return a defined set of files, run the linter, and verify only those files get analyzed—that's integration-level testing. System-level would use actual GitHub PR context. Integration should catch most real failures. So my answers are: Behavior 1 is Integration, Behavior 2 is System, Behaviors 3-4 are Integration, and Behavior 5 is Unit. Now I need to write out the test plan with descriptions and justifications for each behavior, starting with verifying that only changed files get analyzed in the pull request. bugs)\n  - Integration: 0.8 (need real file set and filtering)\n  - System: 0.1 (GitHub API context not strictly necessary if using git diff)\n\nFor findings grouped by severity, I need to verify they're organized by level (error, warning, info) in the PR comment. While the grouping itself could be unit-tested, catching actual failures requires confirming the comment posts to GitHub with the right structure—a mocked API might miss issues like incorrect endpoints or payload formats. I'd set up mixed severity findings, have the linter format and post them, then validate the GitHub comment contains the proper grouping and structure.\n\nThe performance requirement around analyzing 200 files within the 10-minute timeout demands realistic conditions. Unit tests with mocked linters won't expose actual bottlenecks, so I need integration-level testing with real files and actual linter execution to measure timing and catch timeout failures.\n\nFor this test, I'd create a corpus of 200 files with varied types and realistic linting complexity, run the complete pipeline end-to-end, and verify execution stays under 10 minutes while capturing timing details to pinpoint any slowdowns. While a system-level test in the actual GitHub Actions environment would be more ideal, integration testing with genuine file processing and execution measurement is sufficient to validate the performance constraint.\n\nThe fourth behavior involves crash resilience—when the linter encounters a malformed file and crashes, the system should continue processing remaining files and still produce results.\n\nThis requires integration-level testing since mocked subprocess execution would mask the actual crash behavior. I need to use a real linter subprocess with a deliberately malformed input file to verify that the crash is caught, logged, and doesn't prevent analysis of subsequent files. The test should confirm that valid files still get results posted and the error gets noted in the comment. Unit tests with mocks would hide the real exception handling that occurs during subprocess failure, so integration testing is the minimum viable level here.\n\nFor deduplication, findings appearing on the same line from overlapping rules need to be consolidated in the output. This is pure logic with no external dependencies, so unit-level testing works—the test just needs to provide input with duplicate findings on the same line and verify they're consolidated in the output.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":10,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":13330,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"8e087761-80a0-4c28-9f4f-0239ef6d0b14","uuid":"0cc36458-2002-4767-8179-7990b461231c"}
